oups, and 'legitimate' transnational companies. The diamond trade in Sierra Leone has also been subject to exploitation by global business interests, a form of corporate neo-colonialist predation that continues today and which has curbed the country's growth, while recent newspaper headlines also demonstrate the currency of rough diamonds. Sierra Leone's diamonds have been used to finance factions in Lebanon's civil war, criminal networks in the US and Russia, and al-Qaeda. The marginalization and exclusion of Sierra Leone, this book argues, mean that it, and other such resource-rich nations, remain reliant on aid. Diane Frost is Lecturer in the Department of Sociology, Social Policy and Criminology, University of Liverpool  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDiamond industry and trade -- Political aspects -- Sierra Leone. 0aDiamond industry and trade -- Social aspects -- Sierra Leone. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aPolitics & Economics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / African.2bisacsh  aConflict diamonds.  aCorporate neo-colonialism.  aDiamond trade.  aEconomic growth.  aGlobal criminal networks.  aInternational aid.  aResource-rich nations.  aSierra Leone.  aTerrorism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204055240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782040552423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782040552/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles